  "meta": {
    "title": "Cold Seep Mud: Methanotrophs of the Gulf of Mexico",
    "date": "2026-07-24",
    "lesson": "At Gulf of Mexico cold seeps, methane and short-chain hydrocarbons leak from the seafloor into porous, sulfide-rich sediment. Aerobic methanotrophic and methylotrophic bacteria colonize this soft mud, oxidizing methane-derived carbon (here modeled as the lipid/fat class) using methane monooxygenase. They live packed into burrows and pore spaces alongside sulfate-reducing neighbors, competing for the seep's patchy hydrocarbon falls rather than sunlight-driven production. Unlike hydrothermal vents, cold seeps are chemically gentler and much colder, so the community is slow-growing, densely aggregated, and highly locally concentrated around methane seepage points, with grazers and phages persisting for a long time in the cold, food-limited water above the mud.",
    "citation": "Cold seep methanotrophy, Gulf of Mexico continental slope (Joye lab / GC185, GC600 seep sites)",
    "difficulty": "normal",
    "realWorldBasis": "Gulf of Mexico cold seep methanotroph mats (e.g. Bush Hill, GC185)"
  },
